related_questions.question: Is lamb a lamb or sheep?
related_questions.snippet: Lamb is meat from a young sheep, usually under a year to eighteen months old, while mutton comes from an older sheep, often three years old or more.
related_questions.title: Lamb Meat: What's It Called & Why You Shouldn't Eat Lamb

related_questions.question: Is lamb a goat or sheep meat?
related_questions.snippet: In most parts of the world Lamb and Mutton, refers to meat from the same animal: sheep. The only difference is age. Lamb is from a younger sheep (Less than a year old) and mutton is from an older sheep. In South Asian or Caribbean cuisine, mutton refers to the meat of goats.
related_questions.title: Goat Meat: The Succulent Jewel in India's Culinary Crown! - Licious

related_questions.question: What kind of meat is lamb?
related_questions.snippet: Yes, lamb is a red meat. The amount of the protein myoglobin in animal muscles determines the color of meat. Lamb is called a red meat because it contains more myoglobin than chicken or fish. Other red meats are beef, veal, and pork.
related_questions.title: Is lamb a red meat? - Ask USDA

related_questions.question: Is lamb a healthy meat?
related_questions.snippet: Lamb is meat from a sheep that is less than a year old. It is a delicious and rich source of protein that has important vitamins and minerals. When consumed in moderation, it is a healthy addition to a well-balanced diet. Like other red meats, lamb can increase your chances of developing certain chronic illnesses.

buttons.subtitle: What Kind Of Meat Is Mutton?
buttons.title: Lamb vs. Mutton: What's the Difference? - 2024 - MasterClass
buttons.snippet: Mutton is the meat of a mature adult sheep, typically between two and three years old. Producers can harvest mutton from a ewe (female) or wether (castrated male). Since the animal is older, it contains more fat and muscle, resulting in a stronger flavor and denser, tougher texture.
snippet_highlighted_words: the meat of a mature adult sheep, typically between two and three years old

buttons.subtitle: Protein In Lamb
buttons.title: Lamb 101: Nutrition Facts and Health Effects - Healthline
buttons.snippet: The protein content of lean, cooked lamb is usually 25–26% ( 1 ). Lamb meat is a high-quality protein source, providing all nine essential amino acids your body needs for growth and maintenance.

buttons.subtitle: What Does Mutton Taste Like
buttons.title: What Is Mutton? - The Spruce Eats
buttons.snippet: Many people find mutton strong with the musty flavor of grass, hay, and funky soil. It's an acquired taste for some, but it stands up well to bold spices and sauces. However, if the animal was fed on tender spring grass and was younger when butchered, it will have a smoother flavor.
snippet_highlighted_words: musty flavor of grass, hay, and funky soil
